{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01XiumFpnpm9ga5P9j2hHa12","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":664,"cache_read_input_tokens":181663,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":664,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"6c160c6d-f852-4fed-af60-9a462948e048"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01XiumFpnpm9ga5P9j2hHa12","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y17BRkLfG6zbtYmotq2Cvm","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys\ntry:\n    import pypdf\n    with open('/tmp/rc_grpo.pdf','rb') as f:\n        r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n        print('=== RC-GRPO ===')\n        for i,p in enumerate(r.pages[:6]):\n            print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n            print(p.extract_text()[:3000])\nexcept ImportError:\n    print('no pypdf')\n\" 2>&1 | head -200","description":"Extract RC-GRPO PDF first pages"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":664,"cache_read_input_tokens":181663,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":664,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"c86bb9a1-d473-4c6a-9b3c-5ca4ffa550ff"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y17BRkLfG6zbtYmotq2Cvm","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\n=== RC-GRPO ===\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for\nMulti-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nMulti-turn tool calling is challenging for Large\nLanguage Models (LLMs) because rewards are\nsparse and exploration is expensive. A common\nrecipe, SFT followed by GRPO, can stall when\nwithin-group reward variation is low (e.g., more\nrollouts in a group receive the all 0 or all 1 reward),\nmaking the group-normalized advantage uninfor-\nmative and yielding vanishing updates. To address\nthis problem, we proposeRC-GRPO(Reward-\nConditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization),\nwhich treats exploration as a controllable steer-\ning problem via discrete reward tokens. We first\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy\n(RCTP) on mixed-quality trajectories with reward\ngoal special token (e.g., <|high reward|>,\n<|low reward|>) injected into the prompts,\nenabling the model to learn how to generate dis-\ntinct quality trajectories on demand. Then dur-\ning RL, we sample diverse reward tokens within\neach GRPO group and condition rollouts on the\nsampled token to improve within-group diversity,\nimproving agvantage gains. On the Berkley Func-\ntion Calling Leaderboard v4 (BFCLv4) multi-turn\nbenchmark, our method yields consistantly im-\nproved performance than baselines, and the perfor-\nmance on Qwen-2.5-7B-Instruct even surpasses\nall closed-source API models.\n1. Introduction\nTool-using Large Language Models (LLMs) can execute\ncomplex tasks by interleaving natural language reasoning\nwith external API calls (Yao et al., 2023; Schick et al., 2023;\nPatil et al., 2023; Qin et al., 2024). However, for multi-turn\ntool calling, success is often measured by sparse, trajectory-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nlevel rewards, making exploration costly. In this setting,\ngroup-relative policy-gradient methods such as Group Rel-\native Policy Optimization (GRPO) are attractive because\nthey avoid a critic, but their learning signal fundamentally\ndepends on within-group variability: if the rewards within a\nsampled group have near-zero or even completely zero stan-\ndard deviation, the group-normalized advantage becomes\ndegenerate and policy updates vanish.\nA practical failure mode then appears in the standard SFT-\nthen-GRPO pipeline. SFT on optimal demonstrations inten-\ntionally produces a peaked policy (a strong “golden-path”\nprior), which reduces rollout diversity and can substantially\nreduce within-group reward variance under GRPO. This\n“paradox of perfection” is especially severe for multi-turn\ntool calling with partial obser\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nGolden Trajectories\nMixed Trajectories\nSFT Objective\nRCTP-FT Objective\nmin\n𝜃\n෍ − log 𝜋𝜃(𝑎|𝒉)\nmin\n𝜃\n෍ − log 𝜋𝜃(𝑎|𝒉, 𝒓)\n                       \n                 \n            \n                \n              \n        \n                 \n            \n                \n              \n        \n                 \n            \n                \n              \nRollout\n𝜏1, 𝑹𝟏 = 1\nRollout","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"0aeba22c-adf3-4d38-9a5f-9d55355c8c4e","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:05:51.585Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\n=== RC-GRPO ===\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for\nMulti-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nMulti-turn tool calling is challenging for Large\nLanguage Models (LLMs) because rewards are\nsparse and exploration is expensive. A common\nrecipe, SFT followed by GRPO, can stall when\nwithin-group reward variation is low (e.g., more\nrollouts in a group receive the all 0 or all 1 reward),\nmaking the group-normalized advantage uninfor-\nmative and yielding vanishing updates. To address\nthis problem, we proposeRC-GRPO(Reward-\nConditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization),\nwhich treats exploration as a controllable steer-\ning problem via discrete reward tokens. We first\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy\n(RCTP) on mixed-quality trajectories with reward\ngoal special token (e.g., <|high reward|>,\n<|low reward|>) injected into the prompts,\nenabling the model to learn how to generate dis-\ntinct quality trajectories on demand. Then dur-\ning RL, we sample diverse reward tokens within\neach GRPO group and condition rollouts on the\nsampled token to improve within-group diversity,\nimproving agvantage gains. On the Berkley Func-\ntion Calling Leaderboard v4 (BFCLv4) multi-turn\nbenchmark, our method yields consistantly im-\nproved performance than baselines, and the perfor-\nmance on Qwen-2.5-7B-Instruct even surpasses\nall closed-source API models.\n1. Introduction\nTool-using Large Language Models (LLMs) can execute\ncomplex tasks by interleaving natural language reasoning\nwith external API calls (Yao et al., 2023; Schick et al., 2023;\nPatil et al., 2023; Qin et al., 2024). However, for multi-turn\ntool calling, success is often measured by sparse, trajectory-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nlevel rewards, making exploration costly. In this setting,\ngroup-relative policy-gradient methods such as Group Rel-\native Policy Optimization (GRPO) are attractive because\nthey avoid a critic, but their learning signal fundamentally\ndepends on within-group variability: if the rewards within a\nsampled group have near-zero or even completely zero stan-\ndard deviation, the group-normalized advantage becomes\ndegenerate and policy updates vanish.\nA practical failure mode then appears in the standard SFT-\nthen-GRPO pipeline. SFT on optimal demonstrations inten-\ntionally produces a peaked policy (a strong “golden-path”\nprior), which reduces rollout diversity and can substantially\nreduce within-group reward variance under GRPO. This\n“paradox of perfection” is especially severe for multi-turn\ntool calling with partial obser\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nGolden Trajectories\nMixed Trajectories\nSFT Objective\nRCTP-FT Objective\nmin\n𝜃\n෍ − log 𝜋𝜃(𝑎|𝒉)\nmin\n𝜃\n෍ − log 𝜋𝜃(𝑎|𝒉, 𝒓)\n                       \n                 \n            \n                \n              \n        \n                 \n            \n                \n              \n        \n                 \n            \n                \n              \nRollout\n𝜏1, 𝑹𝟏 = 1\nRollout","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01VvZzSftT5ARSRLrnFFmQ71","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SnjBNZ9FxoFKykSHD3EY23","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys, pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/rc_grpo.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages[2:8]):\n        print(f'--- page {i+3} ---')\n        print(p.extract_text()[:3000])\n\" 2>&1 | head -250","description":"Extract RC-GRPO pages 3-8"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1916,"cache_read_input_tokens":182327,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1916,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":55,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"a8ffd056-b36d-4bda-91d6-7813e0c7148a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SnjBNZ9FxoFKykSHD3EY23","type":"tool_result","content":"--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019), reframe reinforcement learning\nas a sequence modeling problem. Instead of estimating\nvalue functions or policy gradients, these methods learn a\nconditional policy π(a|s, R) where R represents the target\nreturn. During inference, the model is conditioned on a high\nreturn value to generate optimal trajectories. This paradigm\nhas been extended to offline RL settings by the Trajectory\nTransformer (Janner et al., 2021), which models the joint\ndistribution of states, actions, and rewards.\n3. Method\nOur method is motivated by a practical pathology observed\nwhen applying group-based policy optimization to strong\ntool-using LLMs. Starting from a high-quality SFT policy,\nrollouts within a GRPO group can become nearly identical,\nreducing intra-group reward variance and weakening the\nrelative-advantage signal. In Sec. 4.3 (Q4 in Sec. 4), we\nformalize this “gradient collapse” phenomenon and show\nhow reward-conditioned rollout generation restores within-\ngroup variance without requiring high policy entropy.\nIn Sec. 3.1, we first formalize multi-turn tool calling as\na POMDP and introduce our reward-conditioned policy\nparameterization. Sec. 3.2 then describes Stage 1, where we\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy (RCTP)\non mixed trajectories labeled by discrete reward tokens.\nSec. 3.3 presents Stage 2, where we optimize the policy\nusing GRPO with reward-conditioned sampling to maintain\nwithin-group diversity.\n3.1. Preliminaries\nWe formalize multi-turn tool calling as a Partially Observ-\nable Markov Decision Process (POMDP). The agent inter-\nacts with the environment until episode termination. At each\nturn t∈ {1, . . . , T max}, the user provides a natural language\nquery ut, and the agent generates an action at, a JSON-\nformatted tool call containing name and args fields. The\nenvironment executes this call and retur\n--- page 4 ---\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nconditioning on <|high reward|> produces optimal ac-\ntions at, while <|low reward|> generates plausible fail-\nures.\n3.3. Stage 2: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative\nPolicy Optimization (RC-GRPO)\nIn Stage 2, we start from the Stage 1 reference policy πref\nand optimize the trainable policy πθ using GRPO with\nreward-conditioned sampling. For each prompt, GRPO\ndraws agroupof G trajectories; we obtain within-group\ndiversity by sampling a discrete reward token r∈ R for\neach trajectory from a fixed distribution Psample(r) (defined\nin Eq. 3) and conditioning rollouts on that token. This in-\njects structured variance into each group—a prerequisite for\nnon-degenerate, group-normalized advantages—and is not\nreliably achieved by temperature/entropy tuning alone when\nπref is highly peaked.\nReward-Conditioned Rollout.For each prompt u0, we\ngenerate a group ofG trajectories {τ1, . . . , τG}. Unlike stan-\ndard GRPO which samples from an unconditional πθ(a|h),\nwe first sample a reward token rj ∼P sample(r) for each\nmemberj∈ {1, . . . , G}:\nPsample(r) =\n(\npifr=<|high reward|>\n1−pifr=<|low reward|> (3)\nHere, p is a hyperparameter set to match the proportion\nof successful (expert) trajectories in the RCTP’s training\ndataset D; the setting of this parameter can be found in\nAppendix B.1.1. This ensures that the sampling prior aligns\nwith the model’s learned distribution, preventing distribution\nshift while still guaranteeing variance injection. Then, for\neach turntin trajectoryτ j, the policy generates:\nat,j ∼π θ(·|ht,j, rj)(4)\nThis steers generation toward diverse quality modes: trajec-\ntories with rj =<|high reward|> tend toward optimal\nactions, while those with rj =<|low reward|> explore\nsuboptimal paths—preventing variance collapse.\nTrajectory-Level Reward Function.To align with the\nunified evaluation framework of modern agentic bench-\nmarks, we adopt a unified trajectory-level reward function\nR(τ) that evaluates the overall success of the interaction.\nThis reward serves dual purposes: (1) constructing the re-\nward tokens r∈ R for building dataset D in Stage 1, and\n(2) calculating advantages during GRPO in Stage 2.\nWe formulate the reward as a composition of two essential\nfactors:\nR(τ) =R state ·R action (5)\nState/Goal Consistency (Rstate).Measures whether the\nagent drives the environment to a correct terminal condition.\nFor BFCL, this compares the final environment state against\nthe state obtained by replaying golden actions (e.g., exact\nmatch of file systems or databases).\nEssential Action / Constraint Coverage (Raction).Mea-\nsures whether required actions and constraints are satisfied\nover the full interaction. For BFCL, we check that every\nessential\n--- page 5 ---\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"87c9dba3-b4db-4c1e-b54f-2e7060426235","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:05:55.091Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019),