{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01KqJe5y6Ez8HwszvK355Vie","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RHSQZwJU3XWL2UynWr9G8V","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys, pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/rc_grpo.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    print('total pages:', len(r.pages))\n    # Look for theory/Prop 4.2 / 4.3 / Tables 1, 2 / Inference-time discussion\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        if any(k in t for k in ['Proposition 4.', 'Inference-time', 'Test-time', 'inference token', '<|high reward|>', 'Decision Transformer', 'Upside-Down']):\n            print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n            print(t[:2500])\n            print()\n\" 2>&1 | head -200","description":"Find key sections in RC-GRPO"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2687,"cache_read_input_tokens":184243,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2687,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":47,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"c89b412c-56f4-4735-8867-68e2ee5c98af"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RHSQZwJU3XWL2UynWr9G8V","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\ntotal pages: 17\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for\nMulti-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nMulti-turn tool calling is challenging for Large\nLanguage Models (LLMs) because rewards are\nsparse and exploration is expensive. A common\nrecipe, SFT followed by GRPO, can stall when\nwithin-group reward variation is low (e.g., more\nrollouts in a group receive the all 0 or all 1 reward),\nmaking the group-normalized advantage uninfor-\nmative and yielding vanishing updates. To address\nthis problem, we proposeRC-GRPO(Reward-\nConditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization),\nwhich treats exploration as a controllable steer-\ning problem via discrete reward tokens. We first\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy\n(RCTP) on mixed-quality trajectories with reward\ngoal special token (e.g., <|high reward|>,\n<|low reward|>) injected into the prompts,\nenabling the model to learn how to generate dis-\ntinct quality trajectories on demand. Then dur-\ning RL, we sample diverse reward tokens within\neach GRPO group and condition rollouts on the\nsampled token to improve within-group diversity,\nimproving agvantage gains. On the Berkley Func-\ntion Calling Leaderboard v4 (BFCLv4) multi-turn\nbenchmark, our method yields consistantly im-\nproved performance than baselines, and the perfor-\nmance on Qwen-2.5-7B-Instruct even surpasses\nall closed-source API models.\n1. Introduction\nTool-using Large Language Models (LLMs) can execute\ncomplex tasks by interleaving natural language reasoning\nwith external API calls (Yao et al., 2023; Schick et al., 2023;\nPatil et al., 2023; Qin et al., 2024). However, for multi-turn\ntool calling, success is often measured by sparse, trajectory-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nlevel rewards, making exploration costly. In this setting,\ngroup-relative policy-gradient methods such as Group Rel-\native Policy Optimization (GRPO) are attractive because\nthey avoid a critic, but their learning signal fundamentally\ndepends on within-group variability: if the rewards within a\nsampled group have near-zero or \n\n--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019), reframe reinforcement learning\nas a sequence modeling problem. Instead of estimating\nvalue functions or policy gradients, these methods learn a\nconditional policy π(a|s, R) where R represents the target\nreturn. During inference, the model is conditioned on a high\nreturn value to generate optimal trajectories. This paradigm\nhas been extended to offline RL settings by the Trajectory\nTransformer (Janner et al., 2021), which models the joint\ndistribution of states, actions, and rewards.\n3. Method\nOur method is motivated by a practical pathology observed\nwhen applying group-based policy optimization to strong\ntool-using LLMs. Starting from a high-quality SFT policy,\nrollouts within a GRPO group can become nearly identical,\nreducing intra-group reward variance and weakening the\nrelative-advantage signal. In Sec. 4.3 (Q4 in Sec. 4), we\nformalize this “gradient collapse” phenomenon and show\nhow reward-conditioned rollout generation restores within-\ngroup variance without requiring high policy entropy.\nIn Sec. 3.1, we first formalize multi-turn tool calling as\na POMDP and introduce our reward-conditioned policy","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"093ba215-dabb-45cf-8a99-4844f14df563","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:06:01.526Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\ntotal pages: 17\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for\nMulti-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nMulti-turn tool calling is challenging for Large\nLanguage Models (LLMs) because rewards are\nsparse and exploration is expensive. A common\nrecipe, SFT followed by GRPO, can stall when\nwithin-group reward variation is low (e.g., more\nrollouts in a group receive the all 0 or all 1 reward),\nmaking the group-normalized advantage uninfor-\nmative and yielding vanishing updates. To address\nthis problem, we proposeRC-GRPO(Reward-\nConditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization),\nwhich treats exploration as a controllable steer-\ning problem via discrete reward tokens. We first\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy\n(RCTP) on mixed-quality trajectories with reward\ngoal special token (e.g., <|high reward|>,\n<|low reward|>) injected into the prompts,\nenabling the model to learn how to generate dis-\ntinct quality trajectories on demand. Then dur-\ning RL, we sample diverse reward tokens within\neach GRPO group and condition rollouts on the\nsampled token to improve within-group diversity,\nimproving agvantage gains. On the Berkley Func-\ntion Calling Leaderboard v4 (BFCLv4) multi-turn\nbenchmark, our method yields consistantly im-\nproved performance than baselines, and the perfor-\nmance on Qwen-2.5-7B-Instruct even surpasses\nall closed-source API models.\n1. Introduction\nTool-using Large Language Models (LLMs) can execute\ncomplex tasks by interleaving natural language reasoning\nwith external API calls (Yao et al., 2023; Schick et al., 2023;\nPatil et al., 2023; Qin et al., 2024). However, for multi-turn\ntool calling, success is often measured by sparse, trajectory-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nlevel rewards, making exploration costly. In this setting,\ngroup-relative policy-gradient methods such as Group Rel-\native Policy Optimization (GRPO) are attractive because\nthey avoid a critic, but their learning signal fundamentally\ndepends on within-group variability: if the rewards within a\nsampled group have near-zero or \n\n--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019), reframe reinforcement learning\nas a sequence modeling problem. Instead of estimating\nvalue functions or policy gradients, these methods learn a\nconditional policy π(a|s, R) where R represents the target\nreturn. During inference, the model is conditioned on a high\nreturn value to generate optimal trajectories. This paradigm\nhas been extended to offline RL settings by the Trajectory\nTransformer (Janner et al., 2021), which models the joint\ndistribution of states, actions, and rewards.\n3. Method\nOur method is motivated by a practical pathology observed\nwhen applying group-based policy optimization to strong\ntool-using LLMs. Starting from a high-quality SFT policy,\nrollouts within a GRPO group can become nearly identical,\nreducing intra-group reward variance and weakening the\nrelative-advantage signal. In Sec. 4.3 (Q4 in Sec. 4), we\nformalize this “gradient collapse” phenomenon and show\nhow reward-conditioned rollout generation restores within-\ngroup variance without requiring high policy entropy.\nIn Sec. 3.1, we first formalize multi-turn tool calling as\na POMDP and introduce our reward-conditioned policy","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
