{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01V6pPAA5kb1hekFTL5sRo7Z","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CN1L8qNr2Vedx8VtzL4bCd","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys, pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/rc_grpo.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        if any(k in t for k in ['Proposition 4.2', 'Proposition 4.3', 'Dirac', 'Theorem 4', 'Inference', 'inference', 'test time', 'test-time']):\n            print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n            print(t[:3000])\n            print()\n\" 2>&1 | head -300","description":"Find theory/inference sections"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2300,"cache_read_input_tokens":186930,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2300,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":56,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"ffc63822-1bc9-466f-ba5d-3357127d1b0f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CN1L8qNr2Vedx8VtzL4bCd","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\n--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019), reframe reinforcement learning\nas a sequence modeling problem. Instead of estimating\nvalue functions or policy gradients, these methods learn a\nconditional policy π(a|s, R) where R represents the target\nreturn. During inference, the model is conditioned on a high\nreturn value to generate optimal trajectories. This paradigm\nhas been extended to offline RL settings by the Trajectory\nTransformer (Janner et al., 2021), which models the joint\ndistribution of states, actions, and rewards.\n3. Method\nOur method is motivated by a practical pathology observed\nwhen applying group-based policy optimization to strong\ntool-using LLMs. Starting from a high-quality SFT policy,\nrollouts within a GRPO group can become nearly identical,\nreducing intra-group reward variance and weakening the\nrelative-advantage signal. In Sec. 4.3 (Q4 in Sec. 4), we\nformalize this “gradient collapse” phenomenon and show\nhow reward-conditioned rollout generation restores within-\ngroup variance without requiring high policy entropy.\nIn Sec. 3.1, we first formalize multi-turn tool calling as\na POMDP and introduce our reward-conditioned policy\nparameterization. Sec. 3.2 then describes Stage 1, where we\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy (RCTP)\non mixed trajectories labeled by discrete reward tokens.\nSec. 3.3 presents Stage 2, where we optimize the policy\nusing GRPO with reward-conditioned sampling to maintain\nwithin-group diversity.\n3.1. Preliminaries\nWe formalize multi-turn tool calling as a Partially Observ-\nable Markov Decision Process (POMDP). The agent inter-\nacts with the environment until episode termination. At each\nturn t∈ {1, . . . , T max}, the user provides a natural language\nquery ut, and the agent generates an action at, a JSON-\nformatted tool call containing name and args fields. The\nenvironment executes this call and retur\n\n--- page 5 ---\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAlgorithm 1RC-GRPO Full Pipeline\n1:Require:Policyπ θ, reference policyπ ref ←π base\n2:Require:DatasetD, training promptsD train\n3: Require:Hyperparameters: learning rate η, KL coeffi-\ncientβ, group sizeG, sampling distributionP sample(r)\n4: Notation: τ= (a 1, . . . , aT ) trajectory; ht history at\nstept;ρ j(θ) =π θ(τj)/πref(τj)importance ratio\n5: // STAGE 1: REWARD-CONDITIONED TRAJEC-\nTORY POLICY (RCTP) FINETUNING\n6: Compute R(τ) for each trajectory τ∈ D (state match\n∧ essential-action coverage; see Sec. 3.3 and App. D) ▷\nEq. 5\n7: Assign a reward token r(τ)∈ R via\nr(τ) =<|high reward|> if R(τ) = 1 , else\n<|low reward|>▷Sec. 3.2\n8: Define LRCTP =−E (τ,r)∼D\nhPT\nt=1 logπ ref(at |h t, r)\ni\n9:Updateπ ref by minimizingL RCTP\n10: // STAGE 2: REW ARD-CONDITIONED GRPO (RC-\nGRPO)\n11:Initializeπ θ ←π ref\n12:repeat\n13:foreach promptu 0 ∈ Dtrain do\n14:forj= 1toGdo\n15: Sample rj ∼P sample(r) and roll out τj ∼π θ(· |\nh, rj)\n16:end for\n17: Compute rewards {R(τj)}G\nj=1 and group-\nnormalized advantages{A j}G\nj=1\n18:Updateθ←θ−η∇ θLRC-GRPO(θ), where\n19:L RC-GRPO(θ) =\n− 1\nG\nPG\nj=1 min\n\u0000\nρj(θ)Aj,clip(ρ j(θ),1−\nϵ,1 +ϵ)A j\n\u0001\n+β D KL(πθ ∥π ref).\n20:end for\n21:untilconvergence\nwhere\nℓclip\nj (θ) = min\n\u0000\nρj(θ)Aj,clip\n\u0000\nρj(θ),1−ϵ,1 +ϵ\n\u0001\nAj\n\u0001\n.\n(9)\nHere ϵ is the clipping range andβ is the KL coefficient. Over\ntraining, πθ improves the expected R(τ) across sampled\nconditions while the clipping and KL regularization stabilize\nupdates.\n4. Experiments\n4.1. Experimental Setup\nWe evaluate our method onBerkeley Function Calling\nLeaderboard (BFCLv4)(Yan et al., 2024) using two base\nmodels:LLaMA-3.1-8B-Instruct(Dubey et al., 2024) and\nQwen2.5-7B-Instruct(Yang et al., 2024).\nCompared Methods.We compare five training configura-\ntions. TheBase Modelis the original instruction-tuned\nLLM without any additional task-specific finetuning on\nBFCLv4. Our three baselines are: (i) supervised finetun-\ning (SFT) followed by Group Relative Policy Optimization\n(GRPO), (ii) SFT followed by reward-conditioned GRPO\n(RC-GRPO), and (iii) reward-conditioned trajectory-policy\nfinetuning (RCTP-FT) followed by standard GRPO. Our full\nmethod combines RCTP-FT initialization with RC-GRPO\nin the RL stage.\nAPI Model Baselines.In addition, we report BFCLv4 val-\nidation accuracy for several closed API models (Opus-4.5,\nSonnet-4.5, GLM-4.7, Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2) evaluated\nunder the same API-calling setting.\nAt inference, we condition on r=<|high reward|>\nfor optimal performance. Hyperparameter configurations\nare provided in Appendix E.\n4.2. Main Results\nWe first present the overall performance of RC-GRPO com-\npared to the baselines. Table 1 reports accuracy on BFCLv4\n(overall and by category).\nOnQwen2.5-\n\n--- page 7 ---\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"7a7aac8b-3fac-4e5e-ad42-eb327b6d9e03","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:06:09.381Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x20f3 for key /Group\n--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nRecent work has highlighted unique challenges inmulti-\nturnagent RL. RAGEN (Wang et al., 2025a) identifies the\n“Echo Trap” phenomenon where agents overfit to locally\nrewarded reasoning patterns, proposing trajectory-level re-\nwards. SimpleTIR (Wang et al., 2025b) addresses training\ninstability from tool feedback deviating from pretrained\ndistributions by filtering void turns during GRPO. Agentic\nRL with Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025) tack-\nles sparse reward credit assignment via implicit process\nreward models. Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\ndemonstrates that LLMs can perform model-based planning\nwhen fine-tuned to predict environment states.\n2.3. Return-Conditioned Learning\nReturn-Conditioned Learning approaches, such as Deci-\nsion Transformers (Chen et al., 2021) and Upside-Down\nRL (Schmidhuber, 2019), reframe reinforcement learning\nas a sequence modeling problem. Instead of estimating\nvalue functions or policy gradients, these methods learn a\nconditional policy π(a|s, R) where R represents the target\nreturn. During inference, the model is conditioned on a high\nreturn value to generate optimal trajectories. This paradigm\nhas been extended to offline RL settings by the Trajectory\nTransformer (Janner et al., 2021), which models the joint\ndistribution of states, actions, and rewards.\n3. Method\nOur method is motivated by a practical pathology observed\nwhen applying group-based policy optimization to strong\ntool-using LLMs. Starting from a high-quality SFT policy,\nrollouts within a GRPO group can become nearly identical,\nreducing intra-group reward variance and weakening the\nrelative-advantage signal. In Sec. 4.3 (Q4 in Sec. 4), we\nformalize this “gradient collapse” phenomenon and show\nhow reward-conditioned rollout generation restores within-\ngroup variance without requiring high policy entropy.\nIn Sec. 3.1, we first formalize multi-turn tool calling as\na POMDP and introduce our reward-conditioned policy\nparameterization. Sec. 3.2 then describes Stage 1, where we\nfine-tune a Reward-Conditioned Trajectory Policy (RCTP)\non mixed trajectories labeled by discrete reward tokens.\nSec. 3.3 presents Stage 2, where we optimize the policy\nusing GRPO with reward-conditioned sampling to maintain\nwithin-group diversity.\n3.1. Preliminaries\nWe formalize multi-turn tool calling as a Partially Observ-\nable Markov Decision Process (POMDP). The agent inter-\nacts with the environment until episode termination. At each\nturn t∈ {1, . . . , T max}, the user provides a natural language\nquery ut, and the agent generates an action at, a JSON-\nformatted tool call containing name and args fields. The\nenvironment executes this call and retur\n\n--- page 5 ---\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nRC-GRPO: Reward-Conditioned Group Relative Policy Optimization for Multi-Turn Tool Calling Agents\nAlgorithm 1RC-GRPO Full Pipeline\n1:Require:Policyπ θ, reference policyπ ref ←π base\n2:Require:DatasetD, training promptsD train\n3: Require:Hyperparameters: learning rate η, KL coeffi-\ncientβ, group sizeG, sampling distributionP sample(r)\n4: Notation: τ= (a 1, . . . , aT ) trajectory; ht history at\nstept;ρ j(θ) =π θ(τj)/πref(τj)importance ratio\n5: // STAGE 1: REWARD-CONDITIONED TRAJEC-\nTORY POLICY (RCTP) FINETUNING\n6: Compute R(τ) for each trajectory τ∈ D (state match\n∧ essential-action coverage; see Sec. 3.3 and App. D) ▷\nEq. 5\n7: Assign a reward token r(τ)∈ R via\nr(τ) =<|high reward|> if R(τ) = 1 , else\n<|low reward|>▷Sec. 3.2\n8: Define LRCTP =−E (τ,r)∼D\nhPT\nt=1 logπ ref(at |h t, r)\ni\n9:Updateπ ref by minimizingL RCTP\n10: // STAGE 2: REW ARD-CONDITIONED GRPO (RC-\nGRPO)\n11:Initializeπ θ ←π ref\n12:repeat\n13:foreach promptu 0 ∈ Dtrain do\n14:forj= 1toGdo\n15: Sample rj ∼P sample(r) and roll out τj ∼π θ(· |\nh, rj)\n16:end for\n17: Compute rewards {R(τj)}G\nj=1 and group-\nnormalized advantages{A j}G\nj=1\n18:Updateθ←θ−η∇ θLRC-GRPO(θ), where\n19:L RC-GRPO(θ) =\n− 1\nG\nPG\nj=1 min\n\u0000\nρj(θ)Aj,clip(ρ j(θ),1−\nϵ,1 +ϵ)A j\n\u0001\n+β D KL(πθ ∥π ref).\n20:end for\n21:untilconvergence\nwhere\nℓclip\nj (θ) = min\n\u0000\nρj(θ)Aj,clip\n\u0000\nρj(θ),1−ϵ,1 +ϵ\n\u0001\nAj\n\u0001\n.\n(9)\nHere ϵ is the clipping range andβ is the KL coefficient. Over\ntraining, πθ improves the expected R(τ) across sampled\nconditions while the clipping and KL regularization stabilize\nupdates.\n4. Experiments\n4.1. Experimental Setup\nWe evaluate our method onBerkeley Function Calling\nLeaderboard (BFCLv4)(Yan et al., 2024) using two base\nmodels:LLaMA-3.1-8B-Instruct(Dubey et al., 2024) and\nQwen2.5-7B-Instruct(Yang et al., 2024).\nCompared Methods.We compare five training configura-\ntions. TheBase Modelis the original instruction-tuned\nLLM without any additional task-specific finetuning on\nBFCLv4. Our three baselines are: (i) supervised finetun-\ning (SFT) followed by Group Relative Policy Optimization\n(GRPO), (ii) SFT followed by reward-conditioned GRPO\n(RC-GRPO), and (iii) reward-conditioned trajectory-policy\nfinetuning (RCTP-FT) followed by standard GRPO. Our full\nmethod combines RCTP-FT initialization with RC-GRPO\nin the RL stage.\nAPI Model Baselines.In addition, we report BFCLv4 val-\nidation accuracy for several closed API models (Opus-4.5,\nSonnet-4.5, GLM-4.7, Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2) evaluated\nunder the same API-calling setting.\nAt inference, we condition on r=<|high reward|>\nfor optimal performance. Hyperparameter configurations\nare provided in Appendix E.\n4.2. Main Results\nWe first present the overall performance of RC-GRPO com-\npared to the baselines. Table 1 reports accuracy on BFCLv4\n(overall and by category).\nOnQwen2.5-\n\n--- page 7 ---\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
