{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Az2HgfibdQLDmV4H8yKSbg","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\nMultiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x2b7cb for key /Group\ntotal pages: 25\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness\nMaximization\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nReinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards\n(RLVR) has markedly improved the performance\nof Large Language Models (LLMs) on tasks re-\nquiring multi-step reasoning. However, most\nRLVR pipelines rely on sparse outcome-based\nrewards, providing little supervision over interme-\ndiate steps and thus encouraging over-confidence\nand spurious reasoning, which in turn increases\nhallucinations. To address this, we propose\nFaithRL, a general reinforcement learning frame-\nwork that directly optimizes reasoning faithful-\nness. We formalize a faithfulness-maximization\nobjective and theoretically show that optimizing it\nmitigates over-confidence. To instantiate this ob-\njective, we introduce a geometric reward design\nand a faithfulness-aware advantage modulation\nmechanism that assigns step-level credit by penal-\nizing unsupported steps while preserving valid\npartial derivations. Across diverse backbones\nand benchmarks, FaithRL consistently reduces\nhallucination rates while maintaining (and often\nimproving) answer correctness. Further analysis\nconfirms that FaithRL increases step-wise reason-\ning faithfulness and generalizes robustly. Our\ncode is available at https://github.com/\naintdoin/FaithRL.\n1. Introduction\nReinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR)\nhas substantially advanced LLM reasoning capabilities in\ncomplex domains such as mathematics and coding (Guo\net al., 2025). However, current paradigms relying on sparse\noutcome-based rewards often neglect intermediate process\nvalidity. Since successfully guessing the answer yields a pos-\nitive reward while explicit refusal is often penalized, models\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nWhen did the headquarters city of the Fireball Cinnamon \nWhiskey manufacturer elect its first black mayor?\nThought Step t: \"New\nOrleans elected its\nfirst female mayor ,\nLaToya Cantrell, in\n2017 .\" Provided Knowledge\n2017\nInitial Output\nEvidence\nFactuality-Driven Methods blindly reward \nfactually\n\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness Maximization\nTo address these challenges, we propose Faithfulness-aware\nReinforcement Learning (FaithRL), a general reinforce-\nment learning (RL) framework that promotes faithful rea-\nsoning. Instead of rewarding only the final answer, it encour-\nages trajectories whose intermediate steps are supported by\nthe required evidence and discourages unsupported steps\neven when they accidentally lead to a correct outcome. Con-\ncretely, we (i) formalizemaximizing reasoning faithfulness\nas an objective and show that it avoids degenerate behaviors\nsuch as over-confidence and over-conservativeness; (ii) de-\nsign ageometric rewardthat balances answering and refusal\naccording to baseline capability, preventing both reward-\nhacking via guessing and blanket refusal; and (iii) introduce\nfaithfulness-aware advantage modulation, which assigns\nstep-level credit by filtering positive updates to faithful steps\nand concentrating penalties on unfaithful ones.\nFaithRL yields consistent gains across benchmarks. Com-\npared with prior RLVR methods, it reduces hallucination\nrates by an average of4.7points while improving cor-\nrectness by1.6points on thefullvariants of 2WikiMulti-\nHopQA (Ho et al., 2020), HotpotQA (Yang et al., 2018), and\nMuSiQue (Trivedi et al., 2022). It also generalizes strongly:\non out-of-distribution tasks such as MATH500 (Hendrycks\net al., 2021) and GSM8k (Cobbe et al., 2021), FaithRL im-\nproves accuracy by over 10.8 points on average and reduces\nhallucination rates by 8.4 points. Finally, FaithRL steadily\nincreases the faithful reasoning ratio during training, im-\nproving the proportion of faithful steps by 31.1% in-domain","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"e1e5147a-377a-4d18-af37-3c5e614379f3","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:06:15.946Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\nMultiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x2b7cb for key /Group\ntotal pages: 25\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness\nMaximization\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nReinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards\n(RLVR) has markedly improved the performance\nof Large Language Models (LLMs) on tasks re-\nquiring multi-step reasoning. However, most\nRLVR pipelines rely on sparse outcome-based\nrewards, providing little supervision over interme-\ndiate steps and thus encouraging over-confidence\nand spurious reasoning, which in turn increases\nhallucinations. To address this, we propose\nFaithRL, a general reinforcement learning frame-\nwork that directly optimizes reasoning faithful-\nness. We formalize a faithfulness-maximization\nobjective and theoretically show that optimizing it\nmitigates over-confidence. To instantiate this ob-\njective, we introduce a geometric reward design\nand a faithfulness-aware advantage modulation\nmechanism that assigns step-level credit by penal-\nizing unsupported steps while preserving valid\npartial derivations. Across diverse backbones\nand benchmarks, FaithRL consistently reduces\nhallucination rates while maintaining (and often\nimproving) answer correctness. Further analysis\nconfirms that FaithRL increases step-wise reason-\ning faithfulness and generalizes robustly. Our\ncode is available at https://github.com/\naintdoin/FaithRL.\n1. Introduction\nReinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR)\nhas substantially advanced LLM reasoning capabilities in\ncomplex domains such as mathematics and coding (Guo\net al., 2025). However, current paradigms relying on sparse\noutcome-based rewards often neglect intermediate process\nvalidity. Since successfully guessing the answer yields a pos-\nitive reward while explicit refusal is often penalized, models\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nWhen did the headquarters city of the Fireball Cinnamon \nWhiskey manufacturer elect its first black mayor?\nThought Step t: \"New\nOrleans elected its\nfirst female mayor ,\nLaToya Cantrell, in\n2017 .\" Provided Knowledge\n2017\nInitial Output\nEvidence\nFactuality-Driven Methods blindly reward \nfactually\n\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness Maximization\nTo address these challenges, we propose Faithfulness-aware\nReinforcement Learning (FaithRL), a general reinforce-\nment learning (RL) framework that promotes faithful rea-\nsoning. Instead of rewarding only the final answer, it encour-\nages trajectories whose intermediate steps are supported by\nthe required evidence and discourages unsupported steps\neven when they accidentally lead to a correct outcome. Con-\ncretely, we (i) formalizemaximizing reasoning faithfulness\nas an objective and show that it avoids degenerate behaviors\nsuch as over-confidence and over-conservativeness; (ii) de-\nsign ageometric rewardthat balances answering and refusal\naccording to baseline capability, preventing both reward-\nhacking via guessing and blanket refusal; and (iii) introduce\nfaithfulness-aware advantage modulation, which assigns\nstep-level credit by filtering positive updates to faithful steps\nand concentrating penalties on unfaithful ones.\nFaithRL yields consistent gains across benchmarks. Com-\npared with prior RLVR methods, it reduces hallucination\nrates by an average of4.7points while improving cor-\nrectness by1.6points on thefullvariants of 2WikiMulti-\nHopQA (Ho et al., 2020), HotpotQA (Yang et al., 2018), and\nMuSiQue (Trivedi et al., 2022). It also generalizes strongly:\non out-of-distribution tasks such as MATH500 (Hendrycks\net al., 2021) and GSM8k (Cobbe et al., 2021), FaithRL im-\nproves accuracy by over 10.8 points on average and reduces\nhallucination rates by 8.4 points. Finally, FaithRL steadily\nincreases the faithful reasoning ratio during training, im-\nproving the proportion of faithful steps by 31.1% in-domain","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01GDMS3Z8XpqNAvMrJCT7LN1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RJxtcGuCNqD2vykCgZ3HnT","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys, pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/faithrl.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        if any(k in t for k in ['CRaFT','Theorem 4.1','Theorem 4.2','Theorem 4.3','x_0','y_0','baseline','offline-validation','validation']):\n            if 'Theorem' in t or 'CRaFT' in t or 'baseline' in t.lower():\n                print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n                print(t[:2500])\n                print()\n                break\n\" 2>&1 | head -100","description":"Find FaithRL theory section"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2232,"cache_read_input_tokens":192624,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2232,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":63,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"46fccf31-282e-42ef-93ed-4a54a370fc53"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RJxtcGuCNqD2vykCgZ3HnT","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness Maximization\nTo address these challenges, we propose Faithfulness-aware\nReinforcement Learning (FaithRL), a general reinforce-\nment learning (RL) framework that promotes faithful rea-\nsoning. Instead of rewarding only the final answer, it encour-\nages trajectories whose intermediate steps are supported by\nthe required evidence and discourages unsupported steps\neven when they accidentally lead to a correct outcome. Con-\ncretely, we (i) formalizemaximizing reasoning faithfulness\nas an objective and show that it avoids degenerate behaviors\nsuch as over-confidence and over-conservativeness; (ii) de-\nsign ageometric rewardthat balances answering and refusal\naccording to baseline capability, preventing both reward-\nhacking via guessing and blanket refusal; and (iii) introduce\nfaithfulness-aware advantage modulation, which assigns\nstep-level credit by filtering positive updates to faithful steps\nand concentrating penalties on unfaithful ones.\nFaithRL yields consistent gains across benchmarks. Com-\npared with prior RLVR methods, it reduces hallucination\nrates by an average of4.7points while improving cor-\nrectness by1.6points on thefullvariants of 2WikiMulti-\nHopQA (Ho et al., 2020), HotpotQA (Yang et al., 2018), and\nMuSiQue (Trivedi et al., 2022). It also generalizes strongly:\non out-of-distribution tasks such as MATH500 (Hendrycks\net al., 2021) and GSM8k (Cobbe et al., 2021), FaithRL im-\nproves accuracy by over 10.8 points on average and reduces\nhallucination rates by 8.4 points. Finally, FaithRL steadily\nincreases the faithful reasoning ratio during training, im-\nproving the proportion of faithful steps by 31.1% in-domain\nand 6.5% out-of-distribution.\n• We propose the novel optimization objective ofmaxi-\nmizing reasoning faithfulness, theoretically proving\nthat it prevents the model from lapsing into over-\nconfidence or over-conservativeness.\n• We introduce FaithRL, a unified RL framework de-\nsigned to strictly align model incentives with this objec-\ntive. To the best of our knowledge, we are the first work\nto propose mitigating hallucinations by directly opti-\nmizing reasoning faithfulness via objective evidence\nverification, laying a foundation for future research.\n• FaithR","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"3a4f08dc-5480-4e71-9630-d970a0595bb8","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:06:21.669Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nFaithRL: Learning to Reason Faithfully through Step-Level Faithfulness Maximization\nTo address these challenges, we propose Faithfulness-aware\nReinforcement Learning (FaithRL), a general reinforce-\nment learning (RL) framework that promotes faithful rea-\nsoning. Instead of rewarding only the final answer, it encour-\nages trajectories whose intermediate steps are supported by\nthe required evidence and discourages unsupported steps\neven when they accidentally lead to a correct outcome. Con-\ncretely, we (i) formalizemaximizing reasoning faithfulness\nas an objective and show that it avoids degenerate behaviors\nsuch as over-confidence and over-conservativeness; (ii) de-\nsign ageometric rewardthat balances answering and refusal\naccording to baseline capability, preventing both reward-\nhacking via guessing and blanket refusal; and (iii) introduce\nfaithfulness-aware advantage modulation, which assigns\nstep-level credit by filtering positive updates to faithful steps\nand concentrating penalties on unfaithful ones.\nFaithRL yields consistent gains across benchmarks. Com-\npared with prior RLVR methods, it reduces hallucination\nrates by an average of4.7points while improving cor-\nrectness by1.6points on thefullvariants of 2WikiMulti-\nHopQA (Ho et al., 2020), HotpotQA (Yang et al., 2018), and\nMuSiQue (Trivedi et al., 2022). It also generalizes strongly:\non out-of-distribution tasks such as MATH500 (Hendrycks\net al., 2021) and GSM8k (Cobbe et al., 2021), FaithRL im-\nproves accuracy by over 10.8 points on average and reduces\nhallucination rates by 8.4 points. Finally, FaithRL steadily\nincreases the faithful reasoning ratio during training, im-\nproving the proportion of faithful steps by 31.1% in-domain\nand 6.5% out-of-distribution.\n• We propose the novel optimization objective ofmaxi-\nmizing reasoning faithfulness, theoretically proving\nthat it prevents the model from lapsing into over-\nconfidence or over-conservativeness.\n• We introduce FaithRL, a unified RL framework de-\nsigned to strictly align model incentives with this objec-\ntive. To the best of our knowledge, we are the first work\nto propose mitigating hallucinations by directly opti-\nmizing reasoning faithfulness via objective evidence\nverification, laying a foundation for future research.\n• FaithR","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01LUgU6Pmnhhz41fnakc3eMi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017ieE45sd8iAVFqhu7H1jbj","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport sys, pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/faithrl.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    # Find pages with 'Theorem' or 'CRaFT' or 'x_0/y_0'\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        if 'CRaFT' in t or 'craft' in t.lower():\n            print(f'--- CRaFT mention page {i+1} ---')\n            # Print local context\n            idx=t.lower().find('craft')\n            print(t[max(0,idx-300):idx+800])\n            print()\n        if 'Theorem' in t and i>2:\n            print(f'--- Theorem page {i+1} ---')\n            idx=t.find('Theorem')\n            print(t[max(0,idx-100):idx+2000])\n            print()\n            break\n\" 2>&1 | head -120","description":"Locate CRaFT lineage and Theorem"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1349,"cache_read_input_tokens":194856,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1349,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":68,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"3206adb5-0b80-4330-a533-2a67192bb9c6"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017ieE45sd8iAVFqhu7H1jbj","type":"tool_result","content":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\nMultiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x2b7cb for key /Group\n--- CRaFT mention page 2 ---\neries. Refusal-Aware Instruction Tuning (RAIT)\nexplicitly trains models to generate specific refusal indi-\ncators for unknown questions, such as outputting ”I don’t\nknow” (Cheng et al., 2024; Yang et al., 2024) or append-\ning uncertainty markers (Zhang et al., 2024a). Although\nadvanced methods like CRaFT (Zhu et al., 2025) attempt\nto alleviate over-refusal by concurrently fine-tuning on\nhigh-certainty and unsolvable samples, these supervised\napproaches may inadvertently constrain general reasoning\ncapabilities. Confidence-based strategies leverage model\nuncertainty to determine abstention decisions at inference\ntime (Jurayj et al., 2025). Implementing these strategies\neffectively necessitates precise calibration techniques (Sun\net al., 2025; Wang et al., 2025a; Damani et al., 2025), and the\nreliance on fixed thresholds can be sensitive to specific task\ndistributions, potentially affecting generalization. Recently,\nRLVR methods have explored incentivizing refusal by penal-\nizing hallucinations through multi-dimensional (Chen et al.,\n2025a) or multi-level rewards (Wei et al., 2025); ne\n\n--- Theorem page 4 ---\n behaviors, optimiz-\ning for reasoning faithfulness aligns refusal decisions with\nmodel capability.\nTheorem 4.1(Asymptotic stability of refusal strategy).\nConsider a model with imperfect intrinsic capability. Opti-\nmizing the three defined objectives leads to distinct asymp-\ntotic behaviors for the miss rateP(M):\n1. Objective A (maximize correctness)forces P(M)→\n0. This results inover-confidence, where the model\nspeculates on all queries to maximize rewards.\n2. Objective B (minimize hallucination)drives P(M)→\n1. This leads toover-conservativeness, causing the\nmodel to refuse answerable queries to avoid hallucina-\ntion risks.\n3. Objective C (maximize reasoning faithfulness)en-\nsuresstability. It maintains the miss rate at a stable\nequilibrium determined by the model’s intrinsic capa-\nbility, effectively preventing the degenerate collapse\nobserved in objectives A and B.\nDetailed proofs are provided in Appendix C.\n4.2. Faithfulness-aware Reinforcement Learning\nWe propose FaithRL, a RL framework designed to maximize\nthe faithfulness objectiveP(F) . To achieve this, FaithRL in-\ntegrates a geometric reward mechanism that aligns outcome-\nlevel optimization with the model’s intrinsic capability, and\na faithfulness-aware advantage modulation strategy that en-\nforces step-level process supervision.\n4.2.1. GEOMETRICREWARDDESIGN\nExisting strategies for optimizing reasoning tasks often rely\non independent metrics for correctness and hallucination,\nwhich may fail to accurately quantify the genuine perfor-\nmance gain after optimization. To simultaneously address\nhelpfulness and honesty without relying on arbitrary hy-\nperparameters, we adopt thetruthful helpfulness score\n(THS)(Zhu et al., 2025) as a higher-order metric that pro-\nvides a geometrically intuitive fusion of utility and honesty.\nAs seen in Figure 3, we represent the model’s capability\nas a point on a two-dimensional plane, where the x-axis\ndenotes the correctness rate and the y-axis represents the\nhallucination rate. Let E0 = (x 0, y0) be the initial capa-\nbility point corresponding to the baseline, E1 be the point\na","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"14a59c8f-3ed1-4b0e-8c17-7b186b0899c9","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:06:27.760Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Multiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x1b06 for key /Group\nMultiple definitions in dictionary at byte 0x2b7cb for key /Group\n--- CRaFT mention page 2 ---\neries. Refusal-Aware Instruction Tuning (RAIT)\nexplicitly trains models to generate specific refusal indi-\ncators for unknown questions, such as outputting ”I don’t\nknow” (Cheng et al., 2024; Yang et al., 2024) or append-\ning uncertainty markers (Zhang et al., 2024a). Although\nadvanced methods like CRaFT (Zhu et al., 2025) attempt\nto alleviate over-refusal by concurrently fine-tuning on\nhigh-certainty and unsolvable samples, these supervised\napproaches may inadvertently constrain general reasoning\ncapabilities. Confidence-based strategies leverage model\nuncertainty to determine abstention decisions at inference\ntime (Jurayj et al., 2025). Implementing these strategies\neffectively necessitates precise calibration techniques (Sun\net al., 2025; Wang et al., 2025a; Damani et al., 2025), and the\nreliance on fixed thresholds can be sensitive to specific task\ndistributions, potentially affecting generalization. Recently,\nRLVR methods have explored incentivizing refusal by penal-\nizing hallucinations through multi-dimensional (Chen et al.,\n2025a) or multi-level rewards (Wei et al., 2025); ne\n\n--- Theorem page 4 ---\n behaviors, optimiz-\ning for reasoning faithfulness aligns refusal decisions with\nmodel capability.\nTheorem 4.1(Asymptotic stability of refusal strategy).\nConsider a model with imperfect intrinsic capability. Opti-\nmizing the three defined objectives leads to distinct asymp-\ntotic behaviors for the miss rateP(M):\n1. Objective A (maximize correctness)forces P(M)→\n0. This results inover-confidence, where the model\nspeculates on all queries to maximize rewards.\n2. Objective B (minimize hallucination)drives P(M)→\n1. This leads toover-conservativeness, causing the\nmodel to refuse answerable queries to avoid hallucina-\ntion risks.\n3. Objective C (maximize reasoning faithfulness)en-\nsuresstability. It maintains the miss rate at a stable\nequilibrium determined by the model’s intrinsic capa-\nbility, effectively preventing the degenerate collapse\nobserved in objectives A and B.\nDetailed proofs are provided in Appendix C.\n4.2. Faithfulness-aware Reinforcement Learning\nWe propose FaithRL, a RL framework designed to maximize\nthe faithfulness objectiveP(F) . To achieve this, FaithRL in-\ntegrates a geometric reward mechanism that aligns outcome-\nlevel optimization with the model’s intrinsic capability, and\na faithfulness-aware advantage modulation strategy that en-\nforces step-level process supervision.\n4.2.1. GEOMETRICREWARDDESIGN\nExisting strategies for optimizing reasoning tasks often rely\non independent metrics for correctness and hallucination,\nwhich may fail to accurately quantify the genuine perfor-\nmance gain after optimization. To simultaneously address\nhelpfulness and honesty without relying on arbitrary hy-\nperparameters, we adopt thetruthful helpfulness score\n(THS)(Zhu et al., 2025) as a higher-order metric that pro-\nvides a geometrically intuitive fusion of utility and honesty.\nAs seen in Figure 3, we represent the model’s capability\nas a point on a two-dimensional plane, where the x-axis\ndenotes the correctness rate and the y-axis represents the\nhallucination rate. Let E0 = (x 0, y0) be the initial capa-\nbility point corresponding to the baseline, E1 be the point\na","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
