{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01QC3uN2tJBRFYDiZM3whBjH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013zx7cZfJ1QiVJ1NBc2ZzAZ","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/vlaw.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    print('total pages:', len(r.pages))\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages[:5]):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n        print(t[:2200])\n        print()\n\" 2>&1 | head -150","description":"Read VLAW first 5 pages"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2760,"cache_read_input_tokens":293705,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2760,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":53,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"941c18a9-fdd4-412a-843f-4d3674798622"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013zx7cZfJ1QiVJ1NBc2ZzAZ","type":"tool_result","content":"total pages: 13\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nVLA W: Iterative Co-Improvement of Vision-Language-Action Policy\nand World Model\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nThe goal of this paper is to improve the perfor-\nmance and reliability of vision-language-action\n(VLA) models through iterative online interaction.\nSince collecting policy rollouts in the real world is\nexpensive, we investigate whether a learned sim-\nulator—specifically, an action-conditioned video\ngeneration model—can be used to generate addi-\ntional rollout data. Unfortunately, existing world\nmodels lack the physical fidelity necessary for pol-\nicy improvement: they are predominantly trained\non demonstration datasets that lack coverage of\nmany different physical interactions (particularly\nfailure cases) and struggle to accurately model\nsmall yet critical physical details in contact-rich\nobject manipulation. We propose a simple itera-\ntive improvement algorithm that uses real-world\nroll-out data to improve the fidelity of the world\nmodel, which can then, in turn, be used to gener-\nate supplemental synthetic data for improving the\nVLA model. In our experiments on a real robot,\nwe use this approach to improve the performance\nof a state-of-the-art VLA model on multiple down-\nstream tasks. We achieve a 39.2% absolute suc-\ncess rate improvement over the base policy and\n11.6% improvement from training with the gen-\nerated synthetic rollouts. Videos can be found\nat this anonymous website: https://sites.\ngoogle.com/view/vlaw-arxiv.\n1. Introduction\nVision-language-action (VLA) models have achieved great\nsuccess in robot manipulation by training on large-scale\ndemonstration data (Intelligence et al., 2025b; Kim et al.,\n2024; Shi et al., 2025; Guo et al., 2025b; Zhang et al., 2024;\nChen et al., 2025). Recent studies further show that VLA\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Lea\n\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"b73cd001-3255-4460-84c5-2e708eda7306","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:35:46.235Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"total pages: 13\n--- page 1 ---\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nVLA W: Iterative Co-Improvement of Vision-Language-Action Policy\nand World Model\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nThe goal of this paper is to improve the perfor-\nmance and reliability of vision-language-action\n(VLA) models through iterative online interaction.\nSince collecting policy rollouts in the real world is\nexpensive, we investigate whether a learned sim-\nulator—specifically, an action-conditioned video\ngeneration model—can be used to generate addi-\ntional rollout data. Unfortunately, existing world\nmodels lack the physical fidelity necessary for pol-\nicy improvement: they are predominantly trained\non demonstration datasets that lack coverage of\nmany different physical interactions (particularly\nfailure cases) and struggle to accurately model\nsmall yet critical physical details in contact-rich\nobject manipulation. We propose a simple itera-\ntive improvement algorithm that uses real-world\nroll-out data to improve the fidelity of the world\nmodel, which can then, in turn, be used to gener-\nate supplemental synthetic data for improving the\nVLA model. In our experiments on a real robot,\nwe use this approach to improve the performance\nof a state-of-the-art VLA model on multiple down-\nstream tasks. We achieve a 39.2% absolute suc-\ncess rate improvement over the base policy and\n11.6% improvement from training with the gen-\nerated synthetic rollouts. Videos can be found\nat this anonymous website: https://sites.\ngoogle.com/view/vlaw-arxiv.\n1. Introduction\nVision-language-action (VLA) models have achieved great\nsuccess in robot manipulation by training on large-scale\ndemonstration data (Intelligence et al., 2025b; Kim et al.,\n2024; Shi et al., 2025; Guo et al., 2025b; Zhang et al., 2024;\nChen et al., 2025). Recent studies further show that VLA\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Lea\n\n--- page 2 ---\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01CagBxzszMrT4Es96CKQvq4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01K9b5JvfLQLn7X9V6yudueC","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport pypdf\nwith open('/tmp/vlaw.pdf','rb') as f:\n    r=pypdf.PdfReader(f)\n    for i,p in enumerate(r.pages):\n        t=p.extract_text()\n        if any(k in t for k in ['Algorithm','39.2','11.6','iterations','iteration','policy','synthetic']) and i>=2:\n            print(f'--- page {i+1} ---')\n            print(t[:2400])\n            print()\n            if i>=6: break\n\" 2>&1 | head -150","description":"Read VLAW method/experiments"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1394,"cache_read_input_tokens":296465,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1394,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"7a11f14a-a297-47f5-b7da-94f1fdb82f3d"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K9b5JvfLQLn7X9V6yudueC","type":"tool_result","content":"--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nVLA W\nVLA Model\nWorld Model\n(1) Real world Rollout (2) FinetuneWorld Model \n(3) Synthetic data Generation\nVLA ModelReward Model\n(4) Advantage WeightedRegression \n1. Learning accurate world model 2. Regularized RL with Expressive Policy\nReal worldDataset\nSynthetic Dataset\n1/20/26, 9:44 PM ﬁg5-2.svg\nﬁle:///Users/yanjiangguo/Desktop/icml2026_ﬁgure/ﬁg5-2.svg 1/1\nFigure 3.Detailed pipeline for VLAW: (1) We first roll out the policy in the real world to collect a small set of online trajectories. (2) We\nthen fine-tune a pretrained action-conditioned world model on these policy rollout data, grounding the world model in the target tasks and\nimproving its predictive fidelity. (3) Using the resulting world model, we generate large-scale synthetic trajectories through closed-loop\ninteractions between the policy and the world model. (4) Finally, we optimize the VLA policy using both real-world and synthetic data,\nwith reward automatically assessed by a vision–language reward model.\nble to train multi-task action-conditioned world models that\ncan generate realistic future visual observations (Chen et al.,\n2024; Gao et al., 2025; Zhu et al., 2024; 2025; Sharma et al.,\n2026). Despite this progress, accurately modeling complex\nphysical dynamics remains a fundamental challenge, as\nwidely observed in prior world-model literature (Guo et al.,\n2025a), likely because these models are trained on offline\nrobotics datasets usually consisting primarily of demonstra-\ntions. To address this challenge, we leverage online policy\nrollout data to ground a pretrained world model in new\nenvironments, thereby improving its accuracy around the\npolicy’s state–action distribution.\n3. Preliminaries\nProblem Setting.We study a multi-task robotic manipu-\nlation problem, where each task is specified by a language\ninstruction I and is modeled as a Markov decision process\n(MDP) MI = (S,A, P, R I , γ). Here, S denotes the state\nspace, A the action space, P(s t+1 |s t, at) the transition\ndynamics, RI the task-dependent reward function, and γ\nthe discount factor. At the beginning of training, we are\ngiven a pretrained vision–language–action (VLA) policy\nπθ and an action-conditioned world\n\n--- page 4 ---\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95e4f6a9-8a56-4158-8f25-24c3b2927cb5","uuid":"bd195a1c-7079-493d-80b7-eafd5b113433","timestamp":"2026-04-27T00:35:51.000Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"--- page 3 ---\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nVLA W\nVLA Model\nWorld Model\n(1) Real world Rollout (2) FinetuneWorld Model \n(3) Synthetic data Generation\nVLA ModelReward Model\n(4) Advantage WeightedRegression \n1. Learning accurate world model 2. Regularized RL with Expressive Policy\nReal worldDataset\nSynthetic Dataset\n1/20/26, 9:44 PM ﬁg5-2.svg\nﬁle:///Users/yanjiangguo/Desktop/icml2026_ﬁgure/ﬁg5-2.svg 1/1\nFigure 3.Detailed pipeline for VLAW: (1) We first roll out the policy in the real world to collect a small set of online trajectories. (2) We\nthen fine-tune a pretrained action-conditioned world model on these policy rollout data, grounding the world model in the target tasks and\nimproving its predictive fidelity. (3) Using the resulting world model, we generate large-scale synthetic trajectories through closed-loop\ninteractions between the policy and the world model. (4) Finally, we optimize the VLA policy using both real-world and synthetic data,\nwith reward automatically assessed by a vision–language reward model.\nble to train multi-task action-conditioned world models that\ncan generate realistic future visual observations (Chen et al.,\n2024; Gao et al., 2025; Zhu et al., 2024; 2025; Sharma et al.,\n2026). Despite this progress, accurately modeling complex\nphysical dynamics remains a fundamental challenge, as\nwidely observed in prior world-model literature (Guo et al.,\n2025a), likely because these models are trained on offline\nrobotics datasets usually consisting primarily of demonstra-\ntions. To address this challenge, we leverage online policy\nrollout data to ground a pretrained world model in new\nenvironments, thereby improving its accuracy around the\npolicy’s state–action distribution.\n3. Preliminaries\nProblem Setting.We study a multi-task robotic manipu-\nlation problem, where each task is specified by a language\ninstruction I and is modeled as a Markov decision process\n(MDP) MI = (S,A, P, R I , γ). Here, S denotes the state\nspace, A the action space, P(s t+1 |s t, at) the transition\ndynamics, RI the task-dependent reward function, and γ\nthe discount factor. At the beginning of training, we are\ngiven a pretrained vision–language–action (VLA) policy\nπθ and an action-conditioned world\n\n--- page 4 ---\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":fa